</p>
<p>P.Â Howe,Â S.Â Devereux,<em> Famine intensity and magnitude scales: A proposal for an instrumental definition of famine.Â </em>Disasters,Â 28Â (1)Â (2004), pp.Â 353-372</p>
<p>
</div>
</li>
<li id="note-33" class="side-matter side-matter-note">
<div class="side-matter side-matter-text">
</p>
<p>This is the general definition offered in Ã GrÃ¡da (2007). Making Famine History. <em>Journal of Economic Literature</em>. Vol. 45, No. 1 (Mar., 2007), pp. 5-38. Available online <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20171208231529/http://irserver.ucd.ie/bitstream/handle/10197/492/ogradac_article_pub_063.pdf?sequence=3">here</a>.</p>
</div>
</li>
<li id="note-34" class="side-matter side-matter-note">
<div class="side-matter side-matter-text">
</p>
<p>Some examples of particularly contentious mortality estimates are discussed below.</p>
<p>
</div>
</li>
<li id="note-35" class="side-matter side-matter-note">
<div class="side-matter side-matter-text">
<p>
See <em>Niger 2005: not a famine, but something much worse</em>, by Gary Eilerts, USAID<br/>
April 2006. Accessed <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20171208231529/http://odihpn.org/magazine/niger-2005-not-a-famine-but-something-much-worse/">here</a>, 25 Aug 2017.</p>
</div>
</li>
<li id="note-36" class="side-matter side-matter-note">
<div class="side-matter side-matter-text">
<p>
See Ã GrÃ¡da (2015) <em>Eating People Is Wrong, and Other Essays on Famine, Its Past, and Its Future</em>, Princeton University Press, 2015, p. 174-5<br/>
The book&#8217;s website is <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20171208231529/http://press.princeton.edu/titles/10449.html">here</a>.</p>
</div>
</li>
<li id="note-37" class="side-matter side-matter-note">
<div class="side-matter side-matter-text">
<p>Available online <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20171208231529/http://www.ids.ac.uk/files/dmfile/wp105.pdf">here</a>.</p>
</div>
</li>
<li id="note-38" class="side-matter side-matter-note">
<div class="side-matter side-matter-text">
<p> As, for instance, in the definition adopted inÂ Ã GrÃ¡da, <em><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20171208231529/http://researchrepository.ucd.ie/bitstream/handle/10197/492/ogradac_article_pub_063.pdf?sequence=3">Making Famine History</a>.</em></p>
</div>
</li>
<li id="note-39" class="side-matter side-matter-note">
<div class="side-matter side-matter-text">
<p> Related to the distinction between <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20171208231529/https://ourworldindata.org/famines/#intensity-vs-magnitude-of-famines">intensity and magnitude</a>Â discussed above. Discussed further in P.Â Howe,Â S.Â Devereux,<em> Famine intensity and magnitude scales: A proposal for an instrumental definition of famine.Â </em>Disasters,Â 28Â (1)Â (2004), pp.Â 353-372 </p>
</div>
</li>
<li id="note-40" class="side-matter side-matter-note">
<div class="side-matter side-matter-text">
<p> And of course it is more likely that such relatively small famines would have gone unrecorded in history in the first place </p>
